{"key":"processedPost-8511079","value":{"id":8511079,"first":8511041,"last":8512707,"when":1213208837,"utime":"06/11/08 09:27 PM","content":"Tiny or non-existant caps are a sure sign of insufficient light.&nbsp; Incandescent is the worst possible light source since it's 'red' with a color temperature of only 3,000 Kelvin.&nbsp; Mycelium pins best with lights that are at the blue end of the spectrum, with a color temperature of around 6,500 K.&nbsp; <br /><br />In addition, incandescent lamps put out 90% of the energy they consume as heat, compounding your problem.&nbsp; Fluorescent tubes put out 90% of the energy they consume as light, which is where you're lacking.<br /><br />Replace the light bulb with fluorescent lights.<br /><br />85% humidity is too low for cakes(or even cased substrates for that matter).&nbsp; Get rid of the silly outdated pop bottle tek and use perlite.&nbsp; You'll get 99% humidity.<br /><br />An hour of light, especially the wrong type of light, is not nearly enough, despite advice noobs will give you to the contrary.&nbsp; Get flourescent lamps and run them roughly 12 hours per day.&nbsp; Mist as required.<br />RR","title":"Re: Pins not forming caps","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}